Basics.HtmlText: Matrix charts show relationships between two or more groups of information in a multi-cross format, illustrating the strength between the different data groups.  For example, this Matrix chart shows the relationship between fuel efficiency, horsepower, engine displacement and acceleration for classic cars manufactured in the 1970s.  Strong relationships were found between engine size and horsepower, engine size and acceleration, and horsepower and fuel efficiency.  Not surprisingly, certain pairings revealed little; for example, there was no relationship between acceleration and  fuel efficiency.  A tooltip helps identify individual points within the Matrix, including the name of the model, country of origin and year of production.

Basics.HtmlText: Quadrant graphs are bubble charts divided into four equal sections and is often used in decision making processes. As with the Matrix chart, a tool-tip offers individual details for car model, country of origin and year of manufacture, alongside information on fuel efficiency, displacement, horsepower and acceleration. For example, if looking for a car with excellent acceleration you don't necessarily require a car, with a big engine although if fuel efficiency is also important, then the less horse power available the better. A trendline overlay shows the underlying relationship between paired factors.
